{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622740"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16822"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76649"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9513"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62146"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8506"},{"type":"tags","id":"10333"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22475"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76649"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinal cord contains both grey and white matter, which are organised into distinct anatomical and functional regions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is found in the grey matter of the spinal cord?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rexed\u0027s laminae","Dorsal funiculi","Lateral funiculi","Ventral funiculi","Dorsal columns"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinal cord is organised into grey matter (containing neuronal cell bodies) and white matter (containing myelinated axon tracts). \u003Cstrong\u003ERexed\u0027s laminae\u003C/strong\u003E are distinct layers of neurons found exclusively in the grey matter of the spinal cord. They are numbered from I to X, with each lamina having specific functions in processing sensory information and motor control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal funiculi\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as posterior columns) are located in the white matter of the spinal cord and contain ascending sensory tracts carrying fine touch, vibration, and proprioception information to the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral funiculi\u003C/strong\u003E are white matter tracts containing both ascending (spinothalamic) and descending (corticospinal) pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eventral funiculi\u003C/strong\u003E are also white matter tracts containing descending motor pathways and some ascending sensory pathways.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edorsal columns\u003C/strong\u003E are another term for the dorsal funiculi, located in the white matter, carrying ascending sensory information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this anatomical organisation is crucial for localising spinal cord lesions and understanding the pattern of neurological deficits that may result from spinal cord injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rexed\u0027s laminae are distinct layers of neurons found exclusively in the grey matter of the spinal cord.","The white matter of the spinal cord contains ascending and descending tracts including the dorsal (posterior) funiculi.","The spinal cord grey matter contains neuronal cell bodies while white matter contains myelinated axon tracts."],"references":["Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Lai HC, Seal RP, Johnson JE. Making sense out of spinal cord somatosensory development. Development. 2016 Oct 1;143(19):3434-3448. doi: 10.1242/dev.139592. PMID: 27702783; PMCID: PMC5087618.","Khalid S, Tubbs RS. Neuroanatomy and Neuropsychology of Pain. Cureus. 2017 Oct 6;9(10):e1754. doi: 10.7759/cureus.1754. PMID: 29226044; PMCID: PMC5718877.","Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62146"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62146"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-03T20:13:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-03T20:13:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9513"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76649"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt"